---
description: Enforce Clean Architecture layer boundaries in .NET projects
alwaysApply: true
globs: ["**/*.cs", "**/*.csproj"]
---

## What This Rule Does

Enforces Clean Architecture dependency rules across all .NET code. Any
generated or reviewed code that violates layer boundaries is refused and the
correct pattern is shown instead. Architecture boundary tests (`*.ArchitectureTests`)
are treated as a first-class build gate, not an optional nice-to-have.

**Memory references:** `memory-bank/architecture.md` (layer rules, module
boundaries for multi-database projects), `memory-bank/backendConventions.md`
(handler/CQRS shape this rule expects generated code to follow).

---

## Layer Dependency Rules (Strictly Enforced)

```
Domain ──────────────────────────── zero NuGet deps (except result primitives)
   ↑
Application ──────────────────────── depends on Domain only
   ↑                                  never Infrastructure, never API
Infrastructure ───────────────────── depends on Application + Domain
   ↑                                  never API
API ──────────────────────────────── depends on Application only
                                      never Domain directly, never Infrastructure
Contracts ────────────────────────── depends on nothing (shared event/DTO types)
```

Violations of these arrows are **refused at generation time** — the agent
will not produce code that crosses a forbidden boundary, regardless of how the
request is framed.

---

## Forbidden Patterns

Each entry shows the violation, the harm, and the correct alternative.

### 1. `DbContext` in Application Layer
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — handler depends on EF Core infrastructure
public class GetOrdersHandler(AppDbContext db) : IRequestHandler<GetOrdersQuery, ...>
{
    public async Task<...> Handle(...) => await db.Orders.ToListAsync();
}

// ✅ CORRECT — handler depends on an interface defined in Application
public class GetOrdersHandler(IOrderRepository orders) : IRequestHandler<GetOrdersQuery, ...>
{
    public async Task<...> Handle(...) => await orders.GetAllAsync(cancellationToken);
}
```

### 2. `HttpContext` in Domain or Application
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — Application handler reading HTTP context directly
public class PlaceOrderHandler(IHttpContextAccessor http) : IRequestHandler<...>
{
    public async Task<...> Handle(PlaceOrderCommand cmd, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var userId = http.HttpContext!.User.FindFirst(ClaimTypes.NameIdentifier)!.Value;
    }
}

// ✅ CORRECT — current user ID resolved in API layer, passed as part of the command
public record PlaceOrderCommand(Guid UserId, IReadOnlyList<OrderLineDto> Lines) : IRequest<...>;
// API layer: var cmd = new PlaceOrderCommand(User.GetUserId(), body.Lines);
```

### 3. Business Logic in Controllers
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> CreateOrder(CreateOrderRequest req)
{
    if (req.Lines.Count == 0) return BadRequest("No lines");
    var order = new Order(req.Lines);
    _db.Orders.Add(order);
    await _db.SaveChangesAsync();
    return Ok(order.Id);
}

// ✅ CORRECT — controller delegates immediately to MediatR
[HttpPost]
[ProducesResponseType<CreateOrderResponse>(StatusCodes.Status201Created)]
[ProducesResponseType<ProblemDetails>(StatusCodes.Status400BadRequest)]
public async Task<IActionResult> CreateOrder(
    CreateOrderRequest req, CancellationToken ct)
{
    var result = await _mediator.Send(new CreateOrderCommand(req.Lines), ct);
    return result.IsSuccess ? CreatedAtAction(nameof(GetOrder), new { id = result.Value.Id }, result.Value)
                            : result.ToProblemDetails();
}
```

### 4. `new SomeService()` Inside a Class
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — breaks DI, untestable, ignores lifetime management
public class InvoiceService
{
    private readonly EmailSender _email = new EmailSender();
}

// ✅ CORRECT
public class InvoiceService(IEmailSender email)
{
    // _email resolved by DI container with correct lifetime
}
```

### 5. Public Property Setters on Domain Entities
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — entity can be mutated from anywhere, no invariant protection
public class Order
{
    public Guid Id { get; set; }
    public OrderStatus Status { get; set; }
    public decimal Total { get; set; }
}

// ✅ CORRECT — private setters, state changes via methods that enforce invariants
public class Order
{
    public Guid Id { get; private set; }
    public OrderStatus Status { get; private set; }
    public decimal Total { get; private set; }

    private Order() { } // for EF Core

    public static Order Create(IReadOnlyList<OrderLine> lines)
    {
        if (lines.Count == 0) throw new DomainException("Order must have at least one line.");
        var order = new Order { Id = Guid.NewGuid(), Status = OrderStatus.Pending };
        order.Total = lines.Sum(l => l.UnitPrice * l.Quantity);
        return order;
    }

    public Result Ship()
    {
        if (Status != OrderStatus.Confirmed) return Result.Failure("Only confirmed orders can be shipped.");
        Status = OrderStatus.Shipped;
        return Result.Success();
    }
}
```

### 6. `IQueryable<T>` Returned from Repository
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — leaks EF Core semantics into Application layer
public interface IOrderRepository
{
    IQueryable<Order> GetAll(); // Application can now build EF queries — wrong
}

// ✅ CORRECT
public interface IOrderRepository
{
    Task<IReadOnlyList<Order>> GetAllAsync(CancellationToken ct = default);
    Task<Order?> GetByIdAsync(Guid id, CancellationToken ct = default);
}
```

### 7. `.Result` / `.Wait()` on Async Code
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — deadlock risk, wastes thread pool threads
var order = _repository.GetByIdAsync(id).Result;

// ✅ CORRECT
var order = await _repository.GetByIdAsync(id, cancellationToken);
```

### 8. Static Methods with Side Effects on Domain Entities
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — static state is global, untestable, hidden coupling
public class EmailService
{
    public static void SendConfirmation(string email) { /* sends email */ }
}

// ✅ CORRECT — instance method, injected, mockable
public interface IEmailService { Task SendConfirmationAsync(string email, CancellationToken ct); }
```

### 9. Swallowed Exceptions
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — failure is silent, debugging is impossible
try { await _repository.SaveAsync(); }
catch (Exception) { }

// ✅ CORRECT — catch specific exceptions, log meaningfully, rethrow or wrap
try { await _repository.SaveAsync(ct); }
catch (DbUpdateConcurrencyException ex)
{
    _logger.LogWarning(ex, "Concurrency conflict saving order {OrderId}", order.Id);
    throw new DomainException("The order was updated by another process. Please retry.", ex);
}
```

### 10. Cross-Layer `using` Directives
```csharp
// ❌ VIOLATION — Domain project must never reference Infrastructure
// In Domain/Entities/Order.cs:
using MyApp.Infrastructure.Persistence; // ← compile error + architecture test failure

// ✅ CORRECT — Domain declares its own interfaces, Infrastructure implements them
// Domain/Interfaces/IOrderRepository.cs — the interface lives in Domain/Application
// Infrastructure/Persistence/OrderRepository.cs — the implementation lives in Infrastructure
```

